{
  "answer": "For Allama Iqbal, *tarbiyat*—translated here as \"training\" or \"nurturing\"—appears in his Urdu poetry as a concept denoting external formation, education, or cultivation, but one that is inherently limited. It cannot improve or perfect a soul lacking innate spiritual quality (*tabiyat* or *jauhar*, i.e., inherent disposition or essence); such training is widely available (*aam*) yet ineffective without an inner spark worthy of divine grace. It also evokes Islamic nurturing (as in being raised in the fold of faith), from which one can still deviate.<sup>[1]</sup><sup>[2]</sup><sup>[3]</sup>\n\nThe term appears directly in the transliterated Urdu text of *Bang-e-Dara* (1924), his major Urdu poetry collection in the Falsafa corpus (no prose works by Iqbal discussing education or self-formation are present). Key instances:\n\n- *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 6 (\"Zamana dekhe ga...\"): Critiquing superficial improvement, nature trumps training: \"Ho tabiyat hi jin ki qaabil, woh tarbiyat se nahin sanwarte\" (\"A soul whose nature is complete, no training can make it more true\").<sup>[1]</sup>\n- *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 4 (\"Dil se jo baat...\"): Divine voice laments: \"Tarbiyat aam toh hai, jauhar-e-qaabil hi nahin\" (\"The training is for all, But where’s the gem to answer to the call?\").<sup>[2]</sup>\n- *Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 24 (\"Tazmeen bar sher-e Aneesi Shamlu\"): Accusing apostasy despite sacred origins: \"Hui Hai tarbiyat aaghosh-e Bait-Ullah mein teri\" (\"You were nurtured in the very arms of the House of God\").<sup>[3]</sup>\n\nIqbal's fuller philosophy of *tarbiyat* (self-cultivation via *khudi*/selfhood) is elaborated in prose works like *The Reconstruction of Religious Thought in Islam* (not in this corpus), but these poetic uses align with his emphasis on inner spiritual rebirth over rote education.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 6, [p-7b7eb7](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/06-zamana-dekhe-ga-jab-mere-dil-se-mahshar-uthe-ga-gu/translation/#p-7b7eb7).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 4, [p-0410a0](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/04-dil-se-jo-baat-nikalti-hai-asar-rakhti-hai/translation/#p-0410a0).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 24, [p-33dc81](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/24-tazmeen-bar-sher-e-aneesi-shamlu/translation/#p-33dc81).",
